- yash-random-y-tst-hangs: `tests/yash/random-y.tst` hangs the testee
  (confirmed via CTest's 120s per-file TIMEOUT actually triggering, not
  just "slow") -- found immediately after re-enabling the
  `tests/posix`/`tests/yash` conformance suites in CMakeLists.txt. The
  rest of the suite (238 other files) completes fine, so this is
  bounded/contained by the existing TIMEOUT property, not a reason to
  disable the suite again. `$RANDOM` itself varies correctly when
  checked directly (`echo $RANDOM $RANDOM $RANDOM` gives different
  values each time), so the two busy-`until`-loops the test opens with
  aren't the obvious suspect; the file's later cases pipe a function's
  output through `print > seeded1; print > seeded2; diff seeded1
  seeded2` inside subshells, which is closer to the shape of the
  already-logged `subshell-exit-trap-output-misdirected` and
  `kill-arg-redirect-parse` bugs (subshell + redirect interactions).
  Not yet isolated to a specific line within the file.

- sh-onsig-async-unsafe: sh_onsig(), the SIGCHLD handler, calls
  term_erase()/term_restore()/buffered i/o directly from signal-handler
  context; none of that is async-signal-safe. Any background job
  finishing exercises the handler, though the unsafety is a latent
  race, not a deterministic per-run failure.

    sleep 1 &
    sleep 2 &
    wait

- fnmatch-bracket-collating-range: a bracket-expression range whose
  endpoints are themselves "[.x.]"-wrapped collating symbols (as
  opposed to bare characters, e.g. "[0-2]") doesn't match as a range
  at all -- lib/path/path_fnmatch.c's range-detection only recognizes
  "X-Y" where X and Y are literal single characters, not
  "[.X.]-[.Y.]"; each "[.symbol.]" gets matched as its own standalone
  member (fixes/67 added support for that part on its own) and the
  "-" in between as a third, literal "-" member, rather than the three
  being fused into a single range. Found while confirming
  fnmatch-p-hang's fix didn't paper over anything else in the same
  test block; POSIX 2.13.1 does define this range form but it's a
  narrow, rarely-used corner of bracket-expression syntax.

    case 1 in [[.0.]-[.2.]]) echo matched;; *) echo no;; esac
    # prints "no"; POSIX says this range covers 0-2, so it should
    # print "matched"

- expand-param-pattern-leading-dot: like the (now-fixed, fixes/82)
  case-statement bug, `${var#pattern}`/`${var##pattern}`/
  `${var%pattern}`/`${var%%pattern}` also pass SH_FNM_PERIOD to
  path_fnmatch() (src/expand/expand_param.c), so a "?"/"*"/bracket
  expression in the removal pattern refuses to match a leading "."
  in the parameter's value, same underlying mistake (this notation
  isn't pathname expansion either, and POSIX 2.6.2 gives it no such
  rule). Found while fixing the case-statement version of this same
  bug and confirmed against bash; not fixed here since it's outside
  that fix's scope (a different function/callsite) and this one
  wasn't in a failing test yet -- probably the very next thing worth
  doing in this area given how similar the fix is.

    X=".abc"
    echo "${X#?}"
    # prints ".abc" (unchanged) -- bash prints "abc"; "?" should match
    # the leading "." like any other single character here

